      "question": "Assertion (A): The denominator of the rational number $17/80$ can be expressed in the form $2^n \\times 5^m$, where $n$ and $m$ are non-negative integers. \\\\ Reason (R): A rational number $p/q$ has a terminating decimal expansion if the prime factorization of $q$ is of the form $2^n \\times 5^m$.",
      "answer": "(A)",
      "solution": {
        "steps": [
          "Find the prime factorization of the denominator $q = 80$.",
          "$80 = 8 \times 10 = 2^3 \times 2 \times 5 = 2^4 \times 5^1$.",
          "Check if $80$ is of the form $2^n \\times 5^m$. Here $n=4$ and $m=1$, which are non-negative integers.",
          "Verify the theorem: A rational number $p/q$ has a terminating decimal expansion if and only if $q = 2^n \\times 5^m$.",
          "Conclude that both A and R are true and R provides the theoretical basis for A."
        ],
        "derivation": "$q = 80 \\\\ 80 = 2 \times 40 = 2^2 \times 20 = 2^3 \times 10 = 2^4 \times 5^1 \\\\ 80 = 2^4 \times 5^1 \\Rightarrow n=4, m=1 \\\\ \\text{Since } q = 2^n \\times 5^m, \\text{ the decimal expansion terminates.}$"
      },
